Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'solid' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity from drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the conventional variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
AIDS disease cannot be cured yet.
However, patients may have a significant life extension of a mixture of medicines that prevent the proliferation of HIV in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus proliferation results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer ineffective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the University of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metal carboranates act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all medicines used today and can therefore overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists come up with new ‘improved' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metal carboranates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polywall cages formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are linked by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and durable virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease due to HIV virus fission, mature infectious viral particles would not occur.
When we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is further systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of anti-HIV protease substances has been tested in the test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants derived from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metal-carborans on the conventional variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of the clinically used drugs, but does not lose its effect on resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modification makes metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research towards the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
