The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching indiscriminate attitudes and mutual scolding -- again on Friday, focused on releasing a document that proposes an ambitious reduction of greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which can provide a way out for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But important progress was seen in negotiations that took place at the wrong time with over 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Created by the UN ad hoc Working Group, this text quietly states how much money rich countries should provide to those poor to deal with global warming both in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies in order to limit their carbon output, and what should be the upper limit of the increase in global temperature that political officials will still be able to tolerate.
This adds a great deal of flexibility to the process, says John Coequyt, Chief Representative of the Sierra Washington Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed a six-page document, crumpled from 180 pages of text from negotiations to focus on what a top climate officer at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture".
It outlines outlines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations could jointly limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent by the year compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during this period.
Together, the country would cut emissions by 2050 between 50 and 95 percent.
The European Union has discussed quickly on Friday the promise that it will provide 3.6 trillion dollars over the next three years to help poorer countries accept climate change adaptation -- ranging from flood management and drought management to preventing deforestation.
