75% of working mothers have motherhood-related work problems.
In recent years, discrimination in employment has increased, especially among women of younger years who intend to have a child.
This is the result of a study of 'The Plodity and Labour Career of Spanish Women' conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 and results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited labour market opportunities due to motherhood.
The study stresses that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in the opinion of the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, formerly deliver the first child and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, partner coexistence and motherhood, delay and have fewer descendants.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have the first child on average 3.7 years since the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted a greater part of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone the cohabitation and arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although a minor influence on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, who is dedicated to research in CSIC.
Another factor affecting women’s age at the time of marriage and the birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age of women getting married and having their first child.
Differences are also between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25,1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with basic education get married and give birth to the first child before they find stable employment, while women with medium or high education go the other way around preferring to get a stable job, before they marry and give birth to the first child", Delgado states.
