The auxiliary system for the handbrake is already mandatory equipment.
As with the ABS anti-lock system, this will also be with ESP stability control, handbrake aid systems, all of which will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others, a deadline is set to address the deficiency, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase the protection of pedestrians, and it works by helping to prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary brake system increases the pressure on the brakes in the emergency case, which the system finds out after the driver steps down.
But it doesn't always hold that pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by Bosch auto parts manufacturer, a third of the drivers who have an accident did not hit the brake before the collision, and half of them did not fully use the brake strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 fatal pedestrian-related accidents per year could be avoided.
The reduction of this number will be even more marked-according to calculations would prevent one of the four accidents affecting persons-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, he will help increase the pressure on the pedal if needed.
If the driver does not respond, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will act as intensively as possible on the brake and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
